segments.text: that if you have a couple of dorms, the girls, you could put your girls in there, or you could put your girls in faculty housing, or if you're really at your worst case, put them in a motel somewhere.
There weren't many motels.
There were one couple across this highway there.
It made the weekends very, very, very special because of the femininity.
You did appreciate the femininity.
And after war the new look would come in and I learned then that you don't have to show a lot of flesh because we walked behind these girls in their hips.

shape, you know, broad where a girl should, well, broad where a broad should be broad, and this thing, this, the curves of the girls were, and the older, and the dressing up, and... Now, during the dance, was liquor allowed in Sabisa?
No, no, no, I don't think so.
You might have, they may have snuck it in.
Yeah, and did anybody smoke inside during the dance?
I don't think so.
I don't think they did.
I don't think so.
I mean, I didn't smoke.
What were Aggies smoking in those days?
Campbells.
I'd walk a mile for a Campbell.
Hellmell, if you were trying to smoke long ones.
Lucky Strike.
Lucky Strike Green.
Scalding War.
World War II.
Did Aggie undergraduates smoke pipes much?
I don't remember.
Cigars?
I don't remember.
Chew tobacco and snuff?
Not much.
I'm not saying nobody did, but I don't remember.
And when they drank, where did they go to drink?
They'd get bottles.
Of course, you'd go up to the— Whiskey bottles.
—the oftentimes the roadhouses, wherever you go, to Onyx, where— Onyx.
Onyx.
That's a new—where was it?
It was on the north side of Bryan.
you know, where the producer's co-op is.
Just at that crossroad.
Okay.
Just as you look at it.
Where Highway 21 is now.
Highway 21 and then the crossroad there over in that area.
There was another across the street there.
that year, and I was trying to get some of the local things here.
Right.
Now, when the air base was in operation, there were some places for sin out there.
Were they still going after the war?
Not as I recall.
Okay.
Of course, the famous Uncle Ed's.
Uncle Ed's.
But I never went out there.
That was beer, wasn't it?
Yeah.
Yeah.
I mean, they didn't have to get their bottles.
They had bottles.
They had to get them from somewhere else.
And then Whiskey Bridge...
Yeah.
Going towards Snook.
Yeah, and you bring your own bottle, buy a Coke, 25 cents a Coke with a Coke smell and a custom nickel.
Get ice and you mix your drink to the table.
And jukebox music.
And doing basically the Texas Two Steps and that kind of dancing out there.
Had you and your buddies ever heard of drugs?
No.
Well, I'd heard of marijuana, but it was a weird thing.
I mean, you know, marijuana.
Had you ever seen anybody smoke it, though?
No, no.

Another difference is that a concert to me was a big orchestra with violins, and you're going to listen to Tchaikovsky and things like that, and you sit there, and you put on Best Bib and Tugger, and you go in there, and it's culture, high culture.
A concert, if you go to a concert, as you go to a concert, it's high culture, not...
They rock concerts that afternoon.
And we had very, very, he went to very, very few concerts a week.
I did go to one because I love Norman Rowe.
He played, and Xavier Cougar played in Guyon Hall.
Just played music, you know, when he was here for a dance on Sunday afternoon or something like that.
And went to that.
Did any notable American heroes come?
Eisenhower came to graduation one time.
Did everybody turn out?
It wasn't a big deal.
Did he say or do anything that was special to Aggies?
He was a pretty low-key individual.
Because I don't remember Truman ever coming.
No, I can't.
Bradley, Patton, I don't remember any of those.
To me, to imagine that at one time Boltshaw Ballet made its home in A&M is an oxygen.
A&M was the last bastion of male chauvinism in my era.
I mean it was different and we were proud of our difference and we were not cultured.
We didn't pretend to be cultured, but we enjoyed life and we were where we were.
As far as you knew, after the war, in the student dorms, were there still the same kinds of pranks and jokes and good bull?
Yeah, maybe worse.
But among you veterans, that didn't occur?
No, no.
We had grown beyond that.
Did you all go to silver taps, you veterans?
Yeah, I think, yeah.
Had it changed because of the experiences that some of them had had during the war?
I don't think so.
I went to one muster.
It was a very low key, low thing over in front of what we called the administration building there.
There weren't many people there.
Had you and your buddies heard about the muster that was held on Corregidor?
I was pretty alert.
This is a note to the typist.

I understand that one of the reasons for that muster being held was that the leadership on Corregidor wanted to get the word out about the survival of as many people as they could and therefore for these Aggies to have muster and to call the roll.
was one way of making that known.
I understand that was one of the reasons why they encouraged that muster.
Let's talk about the student body in general.
What were their attitudes?
Where were they from?
Why did Aggies pull together?
Was there a similarity in the background and attitude?
Yeah, that's right.
I inferred that when I went to the Marine Corps.
I was in with a whole different, asymmetrical group of people.
I mean, thieves, filthy, I mean absolutely filthy talking, acting people, people talking about venereal crabs and things like that.
I don't even know if I've heard of that kind of stuff.
It just was totally different.
But we were all kind of the same type of people.
Small town, generally from the middle, I would say, middle class to upper middle class.
So there were some people of wealth here.
Not too many.
Most of them would go to Texas.
I'd like to diverge here and go and compare my mental image, which I shared with Richard Michael Brown, of the Texas schools at that time, particularly the Southwest Conference schools.
SMU was the school for the children of the Bjork dealer and the Coca-Cola dealer.
of Marshall and all the places.
TCU was the school of the good old boys of West Texas, kind of middle-class, down-to-earth people.
Texas was the establishment school.
The movers and shakers of Texas went there.
Rice was the intellectual school.
And Aggie, Baylor was the Baptist restricted school.
dancing on campus and all that.
A&M was the other sort, the baser sort in a way.
Rough and ready, not much culture in the sense of anything else.
They're people who were intended to build Texas.
Correct me if I'm wrong about Aggies.
If the definition of conservative means
change slowly.
Aggies were conservative.
Aggies were conservative.
And did they...
They're not against change, but conservative before you do it.
Right.
In terms of where they came from geographically, were they comparatively representative of pretty well the whole state?
They were urban and country and small town?
As I said, we had students from
Houston, Lamar, and high school.
We had students from Highland Park.
We also had them from Woodrow Wilson in Dallas that I knew.
And we had them from Austin High School in Houston.
We had them from Thomas Jefferson.
We had them from Hallowell Heights, which was probably one step ahead, socially, culturally, than Jefferson.
But Rocking Ridge and Simple Catholic.
Protestants and Catholics and Jewish?
Protestants and Jewish.
Yeah, and the Jews were mixed right in.
I mean, many of my classmates, most active classmates, I discovered I didn't even think of them hardly then as Jewish.
What were the keys for a student then to become accepted as a part of the group at A&M?
Be able to roll with the punches.
Do their share.
Do their share.
Flexibility.
Show affection.
And when I say that, to this day and age, you may think I mean sexuality.
I don't mean that at all, but that you care somehow about your buddies.
that you share with them.
Let's talk a bit about what builds Aggie spirit.
Why are Aggies so proud?
What is it that creates that spirit?
Why was there a band of brothers going into after Normandy when the
airborne went in and suffered through that.
Why does the Marine Corps put people through very rigorous boot camp and harass them and haze them just as bad as they do here?
There is something in sharing of suffering that we have a shared experience of ardor, of...
We paid a price at that time.
I'm afraid they'll lose it when the price doesn't have to be paid anymore, though I think it lingered down.
And strangely, the people I think that have it the greatest today are the girls at A&M.
Strange that they have more adulation for the Aggie spirit than do guys do.
Now, do these things like muster, bonfire, silver taps, final review, do all of those also add to this pulling together?
The thing, and I regret and I hope, somehow, not on the scale, I'll be frank with you, I blame the administration a little bit for the bonfire catastrophe.
As an Army officer, there would never have been such a project without a safety officer.
Mm-hmm.
I will guarantee you that there should have been a construction engineer taking off one course and put out there to supervise that thing.
There should have been people out there to see that trunking was not permitted, adult human beings.
The one unifying thing I see about university, and I told it at a very small school where the president always talked about the university not being universities, but megaversities.
that was unifying to A&M was the ability of any student at A&M to come and share in this common task of building that bonfire.
Now, they came after my time, I agree.
But I still think it was a good thing.
And I hate to see it go that they can't go out with supervision and cut the logs and do it and not be able to take a cable off without somebody knowing, as they did do.
I think the bonfire is a very unifying thing that you could see it go up, you could participate in being, and then you could share, and it's burning.
And I think it's very good.
I get the distinct feeling, I'll be honest, I get the distinct feeling that the administration uses the traditions as long as for the benefit of the university, and the administration quite often.
But when it comes to cross purposes in any way, they don't make any accommodation.
I'm being real honest as a former student, and sometimes I feel like they use things that I hold very dear, if you understand.
From way back when my brothers, I mean, standing in the Corps of Cadets as a 12, 13, 14-year-old kid,
I thought they got to be very, very, very dear to me.
I got imprinted as you were.
And I mean, as I said before, I knew academically I should go to that school over there.
But I came to A&M for social and cultural reasons, assuming I would get a college education and believing that I could be self-taught to some degree.
All right.
You graduated in the spring of?
49, June of 49.
All right.
But because you had started when you did, what class?
Your class, that's right.
Aggie never loses his class.
That's right.
All right.
So when did you buy your ring?
As soon as I could.
Where'd you get the money?
Had you saved it?
Well, no.
I was on GI Bill.
Two things happened.
First, I got a GI bill, and then I had a contract, got $20 a month.
GI bills started at $40 and then went up to $70.
I started at $50 a month and then $20 for my contract a month.
And then when the contract ran out, I was sports editor of the battalion, and my colleague, we have a mutual admiration society, and I will share this with you.
He went in and bearded the Roman being to get us paid.
So we started getting paid $20 a month for being our dog, the sports editor of the battalion.

Now he admires me because our cadet colonel walked in one time, Bob McClure, with his boots on and all his diamonds on and everything else, very impressive looking, and said in the springtime that we were paying too much attention to things like track and baseball and things like that.
We ought to write more about football.
And he says, I told him, and I don't remember this, but he says, I said, McCrory, you go back and run the Corps, and we'll run the sports page at the target.
Thank you.
And I said, this is their time to participate.
And football has a fall, and we'll write about it.
It wouldn't have spring training or something, but this is baseball track season, and we're going to give them that publicity.
And they have a right to it.
So you go run the Corps, and we'll run the sports page.
Thank you.
Goodbye.
How important was the GI Bill?
Was that a good expenditure of federal money?
Oh, I think fantastic.
Fantastic.
Now, you probably would have gotten your degree anyway, but... My parents would have.
I was invited to...
But a lot of others would not, would they?
Oh, yeah, yeah.
My mother and father would have paid.
I didn't want to ask them for any money.
I wanted to be independent at the time.
I was invited to join Sol Ross when they reorganized...
after the war, but for two reasons, three reasons.
Number one, I had a reputation before the war of being a hard-drinking bunch, and I didn't want to do that.
Number two, I didn't want to spend, I was spending a lot of time on the battalion and doing things.
I didn't want to spend that time in the cell of Ross, whatever they did.
And number three, I didn't think I could afford the uniform, though had I told my mother that I'd been invited to be a member of the cell of Ross, she would have sent me the money in a moment.
The RVs.
The RVs.
Ross Volunteers.
Ross Volunteers, yeah.
When you put that ring on for the first time, do you remember how you felt?
I'm pretty calm.
Other...
Have you ever lost it?
Oh, yes.
This is my second one.
Where'd you lose the other one?
In a moment when the Army disappeared, one of my wife's rings in my ring disappeared.
We were moving from Dallas to Abilene.
And no story about... No.
All right.
I hadn't been ever... Have you ever been someplace unusual where somebody spotted that that was an Aggie ring?
Most unusual thing that ever happened in the life of that, not that particular, but I was in Paris in 19...
51 bachelor in Paris, staying at this small hotel.
There was an English planter from Kuala Lumpur, Malaya, there.
And my son says I was in psychedelic drug stuff.
Couldn't tell him what we did.
And nothing unclean, nothing I couldn't share with my wife or anybody else.
But he told me something.
That's what I heard at one university in the United States.
And I said, yeah.
He said, what's that?
I thought he'd expect to say,
Harvard or Yale or Stanford or some school called Texas A&M.
You ever heard of it?
Yeah, I've heard of it, but it was in agriculture.
And you'd heard of A&M over in Malaya.
But nobody ever did that.
Regular Army, you know, the Army, it was supposed to be, pardon my wife, ring knockers.
But I...
One good thing, I was as confident and as satisfied with being a Texas Aggie as they were with being West Portland graduates.
I was never jealous.
I just read this.
Paul had made some derogatory remarks the other day about the academy graduates.
And I don't understand it.
I mean, hey.
I don't either.
What?
I don't, I mean, I'm, hey, I'm proud of my school.
Sure.
I expect them to be proud of their school.
Yes.
I expect people from Texas to be proud of it.
When I went to the Marines, I was shocked that people were not proud of their state that they were from.
Did you buy senior boots?
No, for reasons.
Number one, because my mother would have bought them for me.
But I was trying to do everything on my own.
I'm very generous, to be honest with you.
But my legs were very, very big.
And senior boots at that time cost $70.
That's a lot of money.
Yeah, a lot of money.
I knew in normal that practice was you buy senior boots and then you sell them.
But with my leg size I didn't think I would be able to sell them.
Nobody would fit, they wouldn't fit anybody.
And number two, you only wore them on special occasions.
And hardly you wore them.
The senior wore them in quarter shoes.
I wasn't, didn't stand out for not having senior boots.
Did anybody ever tease you about not having senior boots?
So that at final review and things like that, those of you who didn't have senior boots just went on.
We were coming out of the Depression, and people understood not having a lot of money.
I mean, we did not live in an affluent society as we live in today, where people could afford a lot of things.
As you were getting ready to graduate in the spring of 1949,
How did you feel about how well you were prepared for the future?
I felt very well.
I felt I had three options, at least three.
Number one was the Army, which I expected to do.
Number two was teaching school.
I had a temporary certificate.
And number three, I thought I could probably get a job in writing sports.
Pretty good writer.
Did any special family and friends come to commencement?
when you graduate?
No, my brother and I graduated all by ourselves.
My parents were in Germany.
Okay.
My aunt didn't come, no.
We were 2,500, biggest graduating class any of it ever had to that point.
Where was the commencement held?
Caulfield in the end zone at Old Horseshoe.
Who was the speaker, was it?
I don't remember.
It was Anna, I wasn't sure I wanted to graduate.
I had another, I thought I had another semester at GI Bill and
Gee, I could use that somewhere, do something, you know.
But then I thought, well, you've got to get on the cold world sometime.
You might as well go ahead and die.
Was every hand shaken and every name called?
You walked across the stage.
Yeah, I walked across the stage.
See, most schools don't do that.
I think that's an extremely important, good, positive last step.
And they pronounced your name correctly and handed you a diploma.
Yeah.
My brother and I graduated at the same time.
He was three years older than I.
He dropped out and came back, dropped out and came back, and he said, boy, he must have really loved A&M.
He entered it about four times.
As you look back, what did you learn at A&M that has been important to you in your life?
Be interested in other people.
Whip out.
It doesn't cost a nickel to reach out and say, my name's Bob Spodey.
And you take out your hand.
If they don't tell you your name, you say, can I have your name, please?
Haskell?
Whatever.
Where are you from?
What kind of work do you do?
Be interested.
Most people want to be approached and ask those things.
I was an introvert.
People find that hard to believe when I was in high school.
But doing that, the Army also helped, and being a Christian helped.
Being interested in other people helped.
As I said, the only time I went to church was when I had a blind date, generally speaking.
And I'd have to do something Sunday morning.
I'd say, honey, not honey, I'd say, Alice, after the dance is on Friday night and Saturday night, I'd say, you know, what do you want to do tomorrow morning, Alice?
Go to church.
So I went to almost every church in College Junction, Catholic, Methodist, Church of Christ, all over the Northgate side.
And there.
Let me, one thing that you don't know is...
getting my regular armed commission.
I was my last semester, Colonel Boatner was the PMSNT.
Hayden L. Boatner.
And son, noted military historian.
I got noticed or appeared before a board over at the YMCA building.
I was, then I was finished by ROTC, I was a civilian, I was wearing civilian clothes.
And I walked over there, got there early, I wanted to scout out the situation, get to feeling comfortable in it.
And I expected a board, like a board of officers, people sitting behind a table, and me on the other side, sitting in a chair.

And I got up there early, I looked around the corner, and here were these three officers sitting in lounge chairs, in there, and they saw me looking around the corner, and said, I just want to come on in.
And I me handed in, I didn't report.
I just thought this was a social conversation.
It was a day after, it was a Wednesday after Truman upset Dewey in 1948.
That was the day it was.
And Colonel Olsen, our branch senior instructor, had said, when you go before that board, the Army's looking for people who are definite.
You can say anything you want to, but be definite about it.
And don't say, I don't know.

don't be wishy-washy and I thought we were having this nice social and they said like Haskell how do you explain Truman defeating Truman doing Walter Lippman didn't know at that stage nobody knew what happened and I said I don't know what do you you know I'm a student in college how am I supposed to know why he won why he didn't win
And they said, do you have a girlfriend?
I said, no, I don't.
They said, why not?
Well, I know, and I knew then, but certain things you hate to articulate.
I could have given them a different answer.
Number one, I knew I wasn't ready for marriage and didn't want to date a girl and leave a girl alone when I didn't want to get married.
And at that age, I was 22, if you date a girl seriously, she's going to be thinking in terms of marriage anyway.
And I just wasn't at that stage.
You can't say that.
So I said, I don't know.
Well, they turned in a pretty unfavorable report to me over to Colonel Boatman.
I got an auditory report to Colonel Boatman.
And I dug a grave a little bit deeper with him.
I went in, and he said, I said, you didn't really impress him with your board meeting.
And I said, no, sir.
And he said, and I went through this a little bit.
I didn't go about the girlfriend or anything.
Then he said, you were in the Marines.
I said, yes, sir.
He said, who was your company commander?
I said, well, sir, I was in the battalion headquarters company, and we never saw our company commander.
I know our first sergeant, I saw him in formation, but never saw the guy.
I don't know who it was.
I'd have worked with Lieutenant Kelly.
And well, who was your battalion commander?
Well, it was a Colonel Wade or a Colonel Dunn, and the S3 was a Major Wade or Major Dunn.
And I could have been fair to him.
I said, well, one of those two.
He said, well, you weren't very alert, were you?
And I said, well, sir, and I thought I'd make some points with this Army colonel.
I dug it.
I said, well, sir, I was anxious to get back in the A&M.
I really didn't think very much of the Marines, sir.
And he said, well, when I was in the Marines in World War I, I thought they were a pretty fine outfit.
And I said,
And then he said, and then he started to find questions.
What's the range of a mortar or a scissor?
You know, all the technical stuff.
And I spit that back at him.
And finally he said, well, Colonel Lawson would recommend you.
I'll go ahead and recommend you to the Red Army Commission.
So I did.
I got it.
But he was a bulldog.
Colonel Malloy and Colonel Bolton.
Let's see.
If you were a consultant to the A&M leadership today,
about the future of A&M, what would be the key points of the advice you would give them?
That's a good question.
Right off the top of my head, do whatever it takes.
to commit.
